(g) Comment more generally on the results obtained. How accurately can we predict the number of college applications received? Is there much difference among the test errors resulting from these five approaches?¶

In [719]:
test.avg <-  mean(Test[, "Apps"])

lm.test.r2 <-  1 - mean((Test[, "Apps"] - pred_line_model)^2) /
  mean((Test[, "Apps"] - test.avg)^2)

ridge.test.r2 <-  1 - mean((Test[, "Apps"] - pred_ridg_model)^2)/
  mean((Test[, "Apps"] - test.avg)^2)

lasso.test.r2 <-  1 - mean((Test[, "Apps"] - pred_lasso_model)^2)/
  mean((Test[, "Apps"] - test.avg)^2)

barplot(c(lm.test.r2, ridge.test.r2, lasso.test.r2),
        col = "gray", names.arg = c("Linear", "Ridge", "Lasso"),
        main = "Test R-squared", las=2, ylim=c(0:1))

Linear, Lasso, and Ridge produce comparable results. Additionally, it reduces the coefficients of other variables and shrinks the Enroll, Top25perc, F.Undergrad, P.Undergrad, Books, Personal, and S.F.Ratio variables to a precise value of zero.

From the graph its clear that every model demonstrates the test R2 of roughly 0.9. Which means all models effectively predict college applications.

Here also we use the CP varibles for the selection, as we can see in the backward the selection the minimum of CP lower that that of the forward's CP.

We can also assess fit by analysing R2 and adjusted r-squared. These are often used in along with Cp to assess model fit. Since AIC is almost similar to Cp we are not considering it here.

set.seed(2312)
regfit.best=regsubsets(V86~.,data=train,nvmax =85, method='forward')

val.errors =rep(NA ,85)
for(i in 1:85){
    coefi=coef(regfit.best,id=i) 
    pred=train.mat[,names(coefi)]%*% coefi 
    val.errors[i]= mean((test$V86-pred)^2)
} 
val.errors

Although they didn't choose the same models, in this case they both discovered the model that reduced the Cp globally.

Forward selection selected model with 27 varibales and backward selection selected model with 38 varibles.

When there are many variables to consider,forward stepwise selection might be employed instead of backward. This is so that unlike backward selection, which must take into account the entire model, forward selection begins with a null model (with no predictors) and adds variables one at a time (which includes all the predictors).

Question 3¶

ESL textbook exercise 2.8 modified: Compare the classification performance of linear regression and k-nearest neighbor classification on the zipcode data. In particular, consider only the 7s and 9s for this problem, and k = 1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13,15. Show the test error for each choice of k. Describe your results are you surprised by the differences in performance?

The zipcode data is available https://hastie.su.domains/ElemStatLearn/ in the Data tab. The data can be obtained as test/training and/or by number.

Subset the train & test data to 7's and 9's only. Then we convert to our desired variables.

In [762]:
train <- train_set[train_set[,1] %in% c(7, 9),]
test <- test_set[test_set[,1] %in% c(7, 9),]
vars <- c("V1", "V3", "V5", "V7", "V9", "V11", "V13","V15")
train <- train[,vars]
test <- test[,vars]

Linear Model¶

In [786]:
linear_model <- lm(train[,1]~., data=train[,-1])
weighted_average <- predict(linear_model, test[,2:8])
lin_pred_vals <- ifelse(weighted_average>2.5, 7, 9)
lin_error_rate <- mean(lin_pred_vals!=test[,1])
In [787]:

kNN Model¶

loading libraries for kNN

By selecting an ideal K by crossvalidation, we might reduce the error rate.

In [803]:
k_vals = c(1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15)

for (i in 1:length(k_vals)){
                knn_pred_vals <- knn(train[,2:8], test[,2:8], train[,1], k=i)
                knn_error_rate <- mean(knn_pred_vals!=test[,1])
                print(paste("kNN error rate when K =",k_vals[i],"is",knn_error_rate))
}
plot(knn_pred_vals)

[1] "kNN error rate when K = 1 is 0.228395061728395"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 3 is 0.212962962962963"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 5 is 0.191358024691358"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 7 is 0.166666666666667"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 9 is 0.160493827160494"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 11 is 0.160493827160494"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 13 is 0.151234567901235"
[1] "kNN error rate when K = 15 is 0.157407407407407"

It is surprising that the test error rates tend to fall as the number of neighbors increases.

The kNN model performs better than Linear model neighbors in this dataset. The Accuracy of kNN model is more than 1.5 times the accuracy of the linear model. But here,there can be chance for outliers as this is large dataset involving large number of feature.
